23 March 1520","1569":"1569","1500":"1500","1478":"1478","1510":"1510","1520":"1520","1498":"1498","1464":"1464","1540":"1540","1580":"1580","Hertford, Hertfordshire,  England":"Hertford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Swinton, Lancashire, England":"Swinton, Lancashire, England","Wrentham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Wrentham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","North Burton, Yorkshire, England":"North Burton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Hertford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smyth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Aidan, Brigid, Conor, Eoin, Malachy, Paddy.","English: variant of   Smith  . This form of the surname is particularly common Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Smith","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne Smyth was born in 1500, in Wrentham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Smythe, was 36 and her mother, Catherine Thorpe, was 36. She had at least 1 son with Richard Ayres Eyres. She died in 1580, in Hertford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1500–1580":"1500–1580","1498–1569":"1498–1569","1510–1540":"1510–1540","1464–1520":"1464–1520","1464–Female":"1464–Surnud","23 Mar 1520":"23. märts 1520","1569":"1569","1500":"1500","1478":"1478","1510":"1510","1520":"1520","1498":"1498","1464":"1464","1540":"1540","1580":"1580","Hertford, Hertfordshire,  England":"Hertford, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swinton, Lancashire, England":"Swinton, Lancashire, England","Wrentham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Wrentham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Burton, Yorkshire, England":"North Burton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hertford, Hertfordshire, England, U